"Luo Y., Liu Q., Rothstein L.M.","Simulated response of North Pacific Mode Waters to global warming",2009,"Geophysical Research Letters","36","23", L23609,"","",,,10.1029/2009GL040906,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-72049114418&partnerID=40&md5=d15dbdd1651047ece8085e3be42fe1b4","Graduate School of Oceanography, University of Rhode Island, 215 South Ferry Rd., Narragansett, RI 02882, United States; Physical Oceanography Laboratory, Ocean University of China, No. 238 Songling Rd., Qingdao 266100, China","Luo, Y., Graduate School of Oceanography, University of Rhode Island, 215 South Ferry Rd., Narragansett, RI 02882, United States; Liu, Q., Physical Oceanography Laboratory, Ocean University of China, No. 238 Songling Rd., Qingdao 266100, China; Rothstein, L.M., Graduate School of Oceanography, University of Rhode Island, 215 South Ferry Rd., Narragansett, RI 02882, United States","This study investigates the response of the Mode Waters in the North Pacific to global warming based on a set of Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change (IPCC) Fourth Assessment Report (AR4) models. Solutions between a present-day climate and a future, warmer climate are compared. Under the warmer climate scenario, the Mode Waters are produced on lighter isopycnal surfaces and are significantly weakened in terms of their formation and evolution. These changes are due to a more stratified upper ocean and thus a shoaling of the winter mixing depth resulting mainly from a reduction of the ocean-to-atmosphere heat loss over the subtropical region. The basin-wide wind stress may adjust the Mode Waters indirectly through its impact on the surface heat flux and subduction process. Copyright 2009 by the American Geophysical Union.",,"Climate scenarios; Intergovernmental panel on climate changes; Isopycnal surfaces; North Pacific; Simulated response; Subduction process; Subtropical regions; Surface heat fluxes; Upper ocean; Global warming; Oceanography; Upper atmosphere; Wind stress; Heat flux; air-sea interaction; global warming; heat flux; Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change; isopycnal layer; mode water; shoaling wave; subduction; subduction zone; upper ocean; wind stress; winter; Pacific Ocean; Pacific Ocean (North)",,,,,,"Boer, G.B., Changes in interannual variability and decadal potential predictability under global warming (2009) J. Clim., 22, pp. 3098-3109. , doi:10.1175/2008JCLI2835.1; Davis, X.J., (2008) Numerical and Theoretical Investigations of North Pacific Subtropical Mode Water with Implications to Pacific Climate Variability, 199p. , Ph.D. dissertation, Univ. of R. I., Kingston; Gu, D., Philander, S.G.H., Interdecadal climate fluctuations that depend on exchanges between the tropics and extratropics (1997) Science, 275 (5301), pp. 805-807. , DOI 10.1126/science.275.5301.805; Hanawa, K., Talley, L., Mode Waters (2001) Ocean Circulation and Climate, Int. Geophys. Ser., 77, pp. 373-386. , edited by S. Siedler, J. Church, and J. Gould, Academic, San Diego, Calif; Hautala, S.L., Roemmich, D.H., Subtropical mode water in the northeast Pacific Basin (1998) J. Geophys. Res., 103, pp. 13,055-13,066. , doi:10.1029/98JC01015; Hosoda, S., Xie, S.-P., Takeuchi, K., Nonaka, M., Eastern North Pacific Subtropical Mode Water in a general circulation model: Formation mechanism and salinity effects (2001) Journal of Geophysical Research C: Oceans, 106 (9), pp. 19671-19681; Hu, Y., Fu, Q., Observed poleward expansion of the Hadley circulation since 1979 (2007) Atmospheric Chemistry and Physics, 7 (19), pp. 5229-5236; Kelly, K.A., Dong, S., The relationship of western boundary current heat transport and storage to mid-latitude ocean-atmosphere interaction (2004) Earth's Climate: The Ocean-Atmosphere Interaction, Geophys. Monogr. Ser., 147, pp. 347-363. , edited by C. Wang, S.-P. Xie, and J.A. Carton, AGU, Washington, D. C; Kubokawa, A., Ventilated thermocline strongly affected by a deep mixed layer: A theory for subtropical countercurrent